figgy.title: Refactor reports controller to use new csv report class

comments.body:
@hackartisan I had a couple of questions about this ticket, for when you have time (I'm back after break, on 3/20, so no rush): 
1. What is the end goal with this refactor? / Could you provide more guidance on what code I should be looking to replace? I wondered if it was some of the CSV class calls at first, but csv_report.rb also uses the CSV class, so I wasn't sure.
2. The new csv_report.rb writes converts the data to CSV format and writes it to a path, but it's unclear to me what the current reports_controller.rb does‚Äîis it also writing the data to a path? 
3. If so, how do I find this path so I can pass it to the new `CSVReport#write`? I see the file name is passed in to `to_csv` in the current controller (lines 20, 32, 47 in reports_controller.rb), which I'm guessing would be the end of the path, but what else should I pass into `Rails.root.join`? (I don't know where the CSV is supposed to end up/can't tell where it's going in the current controller code.)

Thank you! And if it's easier to just talk about this after I'm back, that works too.

@taylor-yamashita great questions! Briefly, 

1. I'd hope to replace the code that does the "turn objects into a csv" work with calls to the new class.
2. the controller sends the csv as a download (see https://api.rubyonrails.org/v7.0.4.2/classes/ActionController/DataStreaming.html#method-i-send_data)
3. We'll probably need to update the new class to be able to provide the csv directly to support this use case. The file name you see on lines 20, etc, is the file name passed to `send_data` as a hint to the browser for what the file should be saved as. 

We can talk more more pair when you're back.

comments.body: This should be completed.  @escowles can you confirm when you get a chance?
üëçüèª yep, I can login now ‚Äî thanks!

I tried to rebase this PR, but there were a lot of commits with merge conflicts, and a lot of them were in the vaulted files.

I would vote for closing this PR and starting again, so we can see more clearly what changes are being made here and what the changes will do.

Could some of this work have interfered with figgy-staging2? It was busted today and it turned out to be a failure to connect to its local redis. We changed the configuration in `/home/deploy/app_configs/figgy` to point to `localhost` instead of `figgy-staging2.princeton.edu` and that fixed it. But that configuration had been working fine for ages.

Also, there are some confusing IPs when you `ping figgy-staging2.princeton.edu` or run `nslookup figgy-staging2.princeton.edu` from the box itself.

```
# ping figgy-staging2.princeton.edu
PING figgy-staging2.princeton.edu (127.0.1.1) 56(84) bytes of data.
64 bytes from figgy-staging2.princeton.edu (127.0.1.1): icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=0.026 ms
```

```
# nslookup figgy-staging2.princeton.edu
Server:         127.0.0.53
Address:        127.0.0.53#53

Non-authoritative answer:
Name:   figgy-staging2.princeton.edu
Address: 127.0.1.1
```

We tell redis to bind to `127.0.0.1` -- if the local ip was redefined it maybe won't find redis anymore?

Update: We looked at `/etc/hosts` and it hasn't been updated since Jan 2020
